  "name": "The 'Charles VI' Tarot (Gringonneur) — c. 1450–1480",
  "description": "# \"Charles VI\" Tarot (Gringonneur)\n\n## At a glance\n\nSeventeen surviving hand-painted trumps held at the Bibliothèque nationale de France,\nhistorically — and **wrongly** — said to be French cards painted in 1392 for King\nCharles VI. They are in fact **Italian**, late-15th-century, and a key witness to the\n**B-order** (Ferrarese) trump sequence. A textbook case of a name preserving an\nexploded myth.\n\n## Origin & dating\n\nThe legend comes from a real account-book entry: a 1392 payment to **Jacquemin\nGringonneur** for three gilded card packs for Charles VI of France. Nineteenth-century\nwriters attached that entry to these cards. But the surviving deck is a **Northern\nItalian** product (Ferrara or possibly Florence), dated to roughly **1450–1480** — about\na century too late to be Gringonneur's. The names \"Charles VI\" and \"Gringonneur\" survive\nonly as labels of convenience.\n\n## Provenance & evidence\n\n17 trumps in the BnF, hand-painted and gilded. Style and iconography place it in the\nFerrarese orbit; its trump order is the main reason it matters — this library places it in the\n**B-order** that Dummett distinguishes from Bologna's A-order and Milan's C-order, **but the classification is genuinely debated**: the cards carry no numerals, and Dummett's own later analysis (*Il Mondo e l'Angelo*) argued the sequence is actually closer to the southern **A-order**, despite the Ferrarese style. A point for the Tarot History Forum to settle.\n\n## Game or divination?\n\n**Game.** No cartomantic use; the divinatory association is, again, a post-1781 import.\n\n## The fear question\n\n**No fear.** A gilded court object of the same luxury class as the Visconti decks. The\nonly \"deception\" in its history is scholarly, not social — the mis-dating, not any\nhidden practice.\n\n## Counter-voices\n\nThe bogus 1392 French date was itself an early piece of **mythmaking** that made tarot\nlook older and more mysterious than it is — a reminder that romantic over-dating (toward\nEgypt, toward medieval France) has repeatedly run ahead of the documents. Correcting it\nis not \"suppressing\" an occult past; it is removing a 19th-century embellishment.\n\n## Open questions / corrections owed\n\n- Ferrara vs. Florence origin is unresolved; date range c.1430s–1470s is still argued.\n- The deck is a fragment; the full original trump set is reconstructed, not observed.\n\n## Sources & further reading\n\n- \"The Fifteenth-Century Charles VI Deck Recreated,\" Tarot Heritage.\n- trionfi.com, \"Origin of Tarot\" notes on the Gringonneur entry.\n- Dummett, *The Game of Tarot* (1980), on A/B/C orders.\n\n---\n*Research notes — AI-assisted first-pass draft, pending review by the maintainer and the Tarot History Forum. Skeptical, document-first (Dummett spine). Corrections welcome via pending edit.*",
